  "business_context": "Donation records hold the executed gift transactions that fund nonprofit operations. Each donation has an amount, a date, a payment method, a donor (Contact or Account), an optional campaign attribution, and a status that distinguishes pledged-but-not-paid (committed) from received (paid). Modeling diverges sharply across systems: CiviCRM uses Contribution as a first-class entity purpose-built for this concept; Bloomerang uses Transaction (and Pledge for committed-but-not-paid); NPSP repurposes Salesforce Opportunity with a Donation Record Type and uses Closed Won = received, Pledged = committed. The B2B systems (Salesforce, HubSpot, Attio, EspoCRM) without nonprofit overlays don't have a Donation entity at all — they have Opportunity / Deal which conceptually maps but operationally requires significant customization (custom record types, custom fields for tax receipt info, custom rollup fields for lifetime giving). Donation records anchor essentially every nonprofit reporting concern: lifetime giving by donor, year-over-year growth, donor retention rate, average gift size, gift frequency, lapsed-donor identification, IRS Form 990 revenue reporting. Acknowledgment-letter generation is typically the most visible automation tied to donations — receipts must go out within IRS-required windows for tax-deductibility. When interviewing clients, surface \"Donation\" by asking how they currently receive and track gifts: by what channels (online, check, stock, in-kind), with what acknowledgment cadence, with what reporting needs (lifetime giving, year-end giving, source attribution by campaign).",
  "catalog_id": "donation",
